Browser2 has the highest count from users and highest count from buyers. Traffictype2 has the most count of users and buyers, second best is Traffictype1. The following rule of thumb is applied to evaluate the correlations between variables:

Correlation coefficient Interpretation
0.90 - 1.00 Very strong correlation
0.70 - 0.89 Strong correation
0.40 - 0.69 Moderate correation
0.10 - 0.39 Weak correation
0.00 - 0.10 Negligible correation

From the correlation plots, For Pagevalues attributes, moderate to strong correlations include:

Relationship Variables
Very Strong correlation ProductRelated/ProductRelated_Duration/(0.86) ;BounceRates/ExitRates(0.91)
Strong correation Administrative_Duration/Administrative (0.62); Informational_Duration/Informational (0.6)

Form Corrplot, the result of strong correlations Variables is quite natural because when users visiting the page of ProductRelated increase the time (ProductRelated_Duration) will increase too. Same as Administrative_Duration/Administrative (0.6); Informational_Duration/Informational (0.62). Also the BounceRates/ExitRates(0.9)when users leave the pages also count in exit rates. Which canâ€™t make any impact for customer purchasing intention.

Relationship (buyers only) Variables(buyers only)
Very Strong correlation ProductRelated/ProductRelated_Duration/(0.84) ;BounceRates/ExitRates(0.9)
Strong correation Administrative_Duration/Administrative (0.61); Informational_Duration/Informational (0.59)

Form Corrplot, the result of buyers strong correlations Variables is quite as same as above.

Data analysis and hypothesis

I am going to discover the relationship between (Administrative, Informational, ProductRelated) number of pages visited by the visitor and the buyers and non-buyers by filter the Revenue and make hypothesis.

H1: Administrative, Informational, ProductRelated number of pages visited by the buyers and non-buyers. Buyers will have higher pages visited.

After removed the data which contain true in Revenue (Non-buyers), We able to see the above boxplot show that Users who is completed transaction usually visited around 5 - 20 pages of Product related, 0 - 3 of Administrative and 0 pages of Informational. Buyers usually visited around 11 - 27 pages of Product related and 0-5 page of Administrative and 0-1 page of Informational. It means that buyers with purchase intention will check more pages then non buyers. when customizing promotions, we may focus on users have higher page visit behavior.

After using the filter function to separate the ExitRates and BounceRates from buyers and non-buyers. We know that buyers have 0.015 to 0.025 ExitRates and 0 to 0.008 BounceRates and non-buyers have higher ExitRates and BounceRates 0.016 to 0.040 and 0.00 to 0.016. It means the users who have buying intention usually not going exit and bounce the pages in higher frequency. Itâ€™s likelihood to people who abandon the page usually higher exit Rates and bounce Rate.

H3 Revenue and Weekend relate to each other.

table(dat$Weekend ,dat$Revenue)
##        
##         FALSE TRUE
##   FALSE  8053 1409
##   TRUE   2369  499
chisq.test(dat$Weekend  ,dat$Revenue, correct=FALSE)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  dat$Weekend and dat$Revenue
## X-squared = 10.582, df = 1, p-value = 0.001142

We have a chi-squared value of 10.582. Since we get a p-Value less than the significance level of 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the two variables are in fact dependent.

H4 Revenue and Month relate to each other.

table(dat$Month ,dat$Revenue)

##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  dat$Month and dat$Revenue
## X-squared = 384.93, df = 9, p-value < 2.2e-16

We have a chi-squared value of 384.93. Since we get a p-Value less than the significance level of 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the two variables are in fact dependent.

We have a chi-squared value of 9.2528. Since we get a p-Value higher than the significance level of 0.05, we reject the H1 that the two variables are relate to each other.

H6 Revenue and Region relate to each other.

table(dat$VisitorType ,dat$Revenue)
##     
##      FALSE TRUE
##   -1    69   16
##   0   9081 1470
##   1   1272  422
chisq.test(dat$VisitorType ,dat$Revenue, correct=FALSE)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  dat$VisitorType and dat$Revenue
## X-squared = 135.25, df = 2, p-value < 2.2e-16

We have a chi-squared value of 135.25. Since we get a p-Value lower than the significance level of 0.05, we reject the H0 that the two variables are not relate to each other.

Form the above test we found that Revenue are relate to Month, Weekend, Visitor Type those Categorical variables We can customized promotions during November and May, which is the most shopping period for shoppers. since the transaction is high is those months. Also, Weekdays have more transaction and we should focus on Returning Visitor.
